>Yes, says Hinton.</p> <p>He says full-time federation officials are paid by the police to carry out union duties.</p> <p><em>Q: Should taxpayers' money be spent on this?</em></p> <p>Hinton says they should be able to represent their members. Police officers do not have normal employment rights, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ef2ce4b0e33c8a560224\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:46:38.375+01:00\">4.46pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Steve McCable</strong>, the Labour MP, goes next. He says the &quot;plebgate&quot; affair has distracted attention from the campaign against cuts.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ee4de4b02b10272e0159\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:45:37.683+01:00\">4.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong> is asking the questions now.</p> <p><em>Q: This was about the cuts. Did you get a letter from the chairman of the national Police Federation (the late Paul McKeever) asking you not to carry on with your campaign.</em></p> <p>MacKaill said he did get a letter. But the Police Federation had no power to tell them to stop.</p> <p><em>Q: The national federation was concerned about the personal nature of your campaign.</em></p> <p>MacKaill says they had the support of their local members, and the public.</p> <p>Vaz says the meeting ended at 5.45pm, even though they had not yet discussed the cuts. He suggests that was because he wanted to get on the evening news.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:53:05.647+01:00\">at 4.53pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ed78e4b0e33c8a560222\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:41:57.944+01:00\">4.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Hinton says he was no there to conduct an interview with Mitchell. He was there to clear the air.</p> <p>He says that when Mitchell said he did not use the words &quot;pleb&quot; or &quot;moron&quot;, that was the first time he had been that specific.</p> <p>Clappison says the officers said that Mitchell did not tell them what he said. But he had done.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-2e3d8e5f-35a7-4da5-8aad-6d05f7b3811b\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382542910109/a578b76c-af4b-44cd-b90f-58b22d6f2853-460x276.png\" alt=\"Stuart Hinton\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Stuart Hinton Photograph: /Parliament TV</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ecc8e4b02b10272e0153\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:38:27.910+01:00\">4.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>James Clappison</strong>, the Conservative, goes next.</p> <p>Q: You said Andrew Mitchell did not tell you want he said. But he did.</p> <p>MacKaill says his comment has been taken out of context.</p> <p>He reads a full version of what he said.&nbsp;</p> <p>MacKail goes on:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>He gave an account but he did not tell us exactly what he said.</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-34caa12b-e471-47d4-81a0-74e513143f42\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382542702332/bf811851-f9a3-4e93-a1e3-bb90d5825cee-460x276.png\" alt=\"Ken MacKaill\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Ken MacKaill Photograph: /Parliament TV</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ec1ee4b02b10272e0151\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:35:31.263+01:00\">4.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Q: Do you think it is in your interests for this to be redetermined?</em></p> <p>Jones says the chief constables have reviewed this.</p> <p><em>Q: So you think all is fine now?</em></p> <p>Hinton says they submitted themselves to an inquiry.</p> <p><em>Q: But the chief constable now wants this reopened.</em></p> <p>Hinton says he did not know that.</p> <p>MacKaill says he would be surprised by that. He would like to know the reasons.</p> <p>Jones says the police should follow due process. He thinks due process has been followed.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267eb97e4b02b10272e0150\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:32:39.389+01:00\">4.32pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Jones has served 28 years in the police, MacKaill 22 years, and Hinton 21 years.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-98eec9ab-3515-40fa-866d-ae4f3eaade58\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382542354865/31399cb7-ceb5-4fd3-a346-776a627d05a3-460x276.png\" alt=\"Chris Jones, Ken MacKaill and Stuart Hinton (l-to-r)\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Chris Jones, Ken MacKaill and Stuart Hinton (l-to-r) Photograph: /Parliament TV</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267eb37e4b02b10272e014e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:30:15.863+01:00\">4.30pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Q: Do you know that the report said you gave a misleading account?</em></p> <p>Jones says he knows that now.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-edde1eb4-c7e6-4b97-af21-7c05aae9486c\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382542203694/da81e85f-715b-4660-b29d-01c2031f927f-460x276.png\" alt=\"Chris Jones\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Chris Jones Photograph: /Parliament TV</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e9dce4b02b10272e0147\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:28:32.533+01:00\">4.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Police Federation evidence</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The three Police Federation officers are here.</p> <p>They are: Sergeant <strong>Chris Jones</strong> from West Midlands Police Federation, Detective Sergeant <strong>Stuart Hinton</strong> from Warwickshire Police Federation and Inspector <strong>Ken MacKaill</strong> from West Mercia Police Federation.</p> <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong> starts.</p> <p><em>Q: You issues an apology. It seems very half-hearted. Is it an apology to Mitchell.</em></p> <p>Jones says the officers did represent that meeting correctly.</p> <p><em>Q: So there is no apology to Mitchell?</em></p> <p>Jones says is an apology for the choreography.</p> <p><em>Q: You think you have done nothing wrong.</em></p> <p>That's right, says Jones.</p> <p>MacKaill says he gave what he thought was an accurate account to the media.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e92ce4b0bdde19a211a5\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:23:03.765+01:00\">4.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">IPCC evidence - Summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>• Deborah Glass, the IPCC deputy chair, has said that she thought the three officers should have been found guilty of gross misconduct.</strong> She said she was surprised when the final report dropped the conclusion that they were guilty of misconduct and instead said there was no case to answer.</p> <p><strong>• She said that she would consider whether there were legal grounds for the IPCC to reopen the inquiry.&nbsp;</strong></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e8b0e4b0bdde19a211a4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:19:48.909+01:00\">4.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong> is asking questions now.</p> <p><em>Q: Is it a good diea for police officers to carry recording cameras, as David Davis recommends?</em></p> <p>Owers says she would not like to extrapolate from one case. But she would point out that when the PACE said interviews should be recorded the police objected. Yet now it is recognised as as good idea.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e81ee4b0bdde19a211a2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:18:04.408+01:00\">4.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Steve McCabe</strong>, the Labour MP, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: Would you says it is &quot;almost impossible&quot; to understand how the police arrived at this decision.</em></p> <p>Glass says the evidence and the conclusion are so at odd she felt the need to issue a statement.</p> <p><em>Q: Do you think Mitchell deserves an apology?</em></p> <p>Glass says she has focused on the misconduct.</p> <p><em>Q: Were you surprised how the police reacted to the Glass statement last week. Some officers said the IPCC should be abolished?</em></p> <p>Owers says she did not hear that.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e7b1e4b027bac8ef9a59\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:15:37.263+01:00\">4.15pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Owers says the IPCC can only supervise certain investigations because of its limited resources. That is unsatisfactory, she says.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-3ebe4369-3180-4d95-ab23-44975f4cd0f6\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382541333017/51675625-747d-4734-bc32-b0bad10c6ded-460x276.png\" alt=\"Anne Owers\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Anne Owers Photograph: /Parliament TV</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e729e4b0bdde19a211a0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:13:39.997+01:00\">4.13pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Julian Huppert</strong>, the Lib Dem MP, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: Why did the IPCC go for a supervised investigation (ie, letting the police investigate this themselves, with supervision from the IPCC), instead of doing it themselves?</em></p> <p>Glass says the IPCC has to live in the real world. It has limited resources. Unlike the police, it cannot just borrow officers from forces.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I would have loved to have done it. But it just was not practical.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e5fbe4b0bdde19a2119c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:11:26.609+01:00\">4.11pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Mark Reckless</strong>, a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: The final report says the IO [investigation officer] thought there was no case to answer. Who did you take that to be?</em></p> <p>Glass says she would have taken that to refer to Jerry Reakes-Williams.</p> <p>She says the authorities would have been entitled to ignore his recommendation.</p> <p>The conclusions were &quot;extraordinary&quot;, she says.</p> <p><em>Q: Why did the IPCC take over the investigation?</em></p> <p>Glass says that to do that just to rewrite the conclusions would have been an abuse of process.</p> <p>She says if there is a way of reopening it lawfully, she would.</p> <p><em>Q: If the chief constables say to us they would like the IPCC to now deal with this, you will take legal advice to see if you can do this?</em></p> <p>Glass says she will look into this.</p> <p>The chief constables themselves definitely can reopen this investigation, she says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e548e4b0bdde19a2119a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:06:30.985+01:00\">4.06pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Nicola Blackwood,</strong> a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p>Glass says nothing gave her concern until she saw the final report on 28 August recommending no further action.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e47ee4b027bac8ef9a54\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:03:29.625+01:00\">4.03pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Michael Ellis,</strong> a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: The investigating officer came to a conclusion. But he was usurped. Is this a whitewash?</em></p> <p>Glass says we are certainly dealing with confusion.</p> <p><em>Q: But do you feel that this is an attempt at a whitewash? In your statement last week you said the Police Federation were running a political campaign.</em></p> <p>Glass says she thinks the conclusions were wrong.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e3d8e4b027bac8ef9a53\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T16:00:05.337+01:00\">4.00pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Chris Ruane</strong>, the Labour MP, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: Mitchell had a 45-second conversation. This has now gone on for a year. Is that too long?</em></p> <p>Glass says the IPCC did not deal with the Number 10 incident. That was investigated by the Metropolitan Police.</p> <p>Owers says the IPCC has limited reources.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-0e37b22b-9c73-4a46-95e8-3a5c05b3a481\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382540392768/35d99e36-8648-4337-8e29-371d6818a212-460x276.png\" alt=\"Deborah Glass\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Deborah Glass Photograph: /Parliament TV</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e385e4b0bdde19a21198\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:56:29.602+01:00\">3.56pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Owers says the appropriate authorities knew what Glass's view was.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e329e4b0bdde19a21196\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:56:01.302+01:00\">3.56pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>James Clappison,</strong> a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p>He quotes from a letter from Andy Parker, the Warwickshire chief constable, saying there were irregularities with the investigation.</p> <p>Glass says she was not aware of that at the time.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e2b9e4b0bdde19a21193\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:54:24.206+01:00\">3.54pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Asked if she thought Andrew Mitchell gave a full account of what happened to the officers, she says he answered all the questions he was asked.</p> <p>The point about not giving a full account sounds like an ex post facto argument, she says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e13be4b0bdde19a21191\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:52:34.181+01:00\">3.52pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Evidence from the IPCC</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Dame Anne Owers</strong>, the IPCC chair, and <strong>Deborah Glass,</strong> the IPCC deputy chair, are giving evidence now.</p> <p>Glass says she thinks the report should have found the three guilty of gross misconduct.</p> <p><em>Q: Do you think they lied?</em></p> <p>Glass reads from the statement she put out last week. A misconduct should have determined that, she says.</p> <p><em>Q: You have been doing this for 13 years. Is there any precedent for a draft report saying misconduct, your advising gross misconduct, and then the final report being even weaker.</em></p> <p>Glass says it is not unusual for reports to change from draft to final version.</p> <p>But in this case she could not see how the conclusion was justified.</p> <p><em>Q: Do you think the IPCC should have carried out the investigation itself?</em></p> <p>Glass says she had no problem with the way the inquiry was carried out. It was just the conclusion she could not accept. She took legal advice on what she could do. That led to her putting out her statement.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267e052e4b0bdde19a21190\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:46:11.208+01:00\">3.46pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Jerry Reakes-Williams' evidence - Summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here is a snap summary,</p> <p><strong>• Keith Vaz has said that David Shaw, the West Mercia chief constable, has now changed his mind about whether the three officers should face disciplinary action.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Jerry Reakes-Williams, the Professional Standards officer who investigated the three officers, has confirmed that he originally concluded the officers were guilty of misconduct, but that he was overruled.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Reakes-Williams has said that he did not think the officers deliberately lied about their meeting with Andrew Mitchell.</strong></p> <p>We are now on to the IPCC witnesses.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267dfcee4b0bdde19a2118f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:42:11.883+01:00\">3.42pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong> says RW has been very open.</p> <p>But the public will conclude you thought there was misconduct, you had a meeting with two deputy chief constables, and then that recommendation was removed.</p> <p>He says the chief constable of West Mercia has submitted evidence to the committee saying there was evidence of misconduct. It backs up what RW said. That will be published by the committee at 5.30, Vaz says.</p> <p>RW says no one put pressure on him to change his stance.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267df74e4b0bdde19a2118d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:40:07.294+01:00\">3.40pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <strong>Steve McCabe</strong> goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: How would you rate yourself as an investigator?</em></p> <p>RW says there may have been procedural issues. But at the time no one picked these up at the time, including the IPCC.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267de34e4b027bac8ef9a4b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:37:23.938+01:00\">3.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Mark Reckless</strong>, a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: The IPCC told you not to share your conclusions with the authorities (representatives of the chief constable). But you did . Why?</em></p> <p>RW says he thought it was important that they were aware of the difference of opinion.</p> <p><em>Q: But you were the investigating officer?</em></p> <p>RW says it was clear he was the investigation officer. But in police terms his deputy may have been seen as the investigating officer.</p> <p>He says the IPCC told him to forward a copy of his report without the conclusions.</p> <p><em>Q: But you disobeyed that instruction?</em></p> <p>Yes, says RW.</p> <p><em>Q: And you are supposed to include all matters in a report that you see fit.</em></p> <p>RW says he was acting with the full knowledge of the IPCC, and of his legal adviser.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267dda8e4b0bdde19a21188\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:33:16.437+01:00\">3.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <strong>Chris Ruane</strong> goes next.</p> <p>Q: Are you sure minutes were not taken at the meeting with the deputy chief constables?</p> <p>RW says he took action points at all his meetings with the IPCC.</p> <p>Q: It is extraordinary that no one took notes?</p> <p>RW says it is easy to be wise with hindsight. He took notes in his policy file.</p> <p>Keith Vaz asks for a copy of those notes.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267dd11e4b027bac8ef9a48\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:30:56.342+01:00\">3.30pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <strong>David Winnick</strong> goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: Is there anything else Mitchell could have said at the meeting?</em></p> <p>RW says Mitchell was clear about what he did not say. But there is &quot;doubt&quot; about whether he gave a full account of everything said between him and the officers at Downing Street at the meeting with the Police Federation.</p> <p>That is why RW concluded that the officers were not guilty of gross misconduct,he says.</p> <p><em>Q: So you are saying there remains a question mark over what happened in Downing Street?</em></p> <p>Absolutely, says RW.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267dc4de4b0bdde19a21187\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:28:26.944+01:00\">3.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><em>Q: The Gaunt Brothers (a PR firm) issued a statement on behalf of the Police Federation officers before the meeting with Mitchell. Does not that suggest premeditation?</em></p> <p>RW says his investigation had a very narrow remit. He was asked to establish if the offices gave a false account of their meeting with Mitchell.</p> <p><em>Q: What is the worst thing that can happen to someone guilty of misconduct?</em></p> <p>A final written warning, says RW.</p> <p><em>Q: And what is the worst punishment for gross misconduct?</em></p> <p>Dismissal, says RW.</p> <p>Q: And is there anything less serious than misconduct.</p> <p>Management action, says RW.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267db7ee4b027bac8ef9a44\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:25:14.530+01:00\">3.25pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Nicola Blackwood,</strong> a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p>RW says he thinks there is doubt as to whether Mitchell gave a &quot;full account&quot; of what he said at Number 10 in the meeting with the Police Federation. In a later interview in the Telegraph Mitchell provided details that he did not give to the three Police Federation offices. On that basis you could argue that he did not give them a &quot;full account&quot;.</p> <p>RW says he is surprised that the officers did not press Mitchell for more detail of what happened in Downing Street.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267db5ee4b0bdde19a21186\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:21:41.168+01:00\">3.21pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Vaz is going on about the lack of a note. He seems surprised.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267dac3e4b027bac8ef9a42\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:21:10.286+01:00\">3.21pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong> goes next.</p> <p>He asks if there was a minute of the meeting between RW and representatives of the three chief constables.</p> <p>RW says he would have taken a note in his policy book.</p> <p><em>Q: Were official minutes taken?</em></p> <p>No, says RW.</p> <p>Vaz says for a meeting with two deputy chief constables, and a legal adviser, somebody would have made a note.</p> <p>RW consults his notebook. It's his policy book, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267da10e4b0bdde19a21184\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:18:36.187+01:00\">3.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>James Clappison</strong>, a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: Did you make it clear to all three forces (represented by deputy chief constables in two cases) that there should be disciplinary action?</em></p> <p>Yes, says RW.</p> <p>He says he does not agree with their decision.</p> <p>But he understands their reasons.</p> <p>Clappison quotes from RW's report. RW said the officers gave an account of the meeting with Mitchell that was &quot;inaccurate and misleading&quot;.</p> <p><em>Q: Your views were left hanging in the wind?</em></p> <p>RW says he works in a disciplined organisation. Sometimes you do not agree with every decision. But a collective decision has to be taken.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267d985e4b027bac8ef9a3d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:14:52.347+01:00\">3.14pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Julian Huppert</strong>, the Lib Dem MP, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: Several changes were made to you report. Why?</em></p> <p>RW says it is common to change the words of a report.</p> <p><em>Q: In every single case the changes made had the effect of softening the report.</em></p> <p>RW says he could not be sure. But the final report had to reflect the views of the appropriate authorities.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267d889e4b0bdde19a2117f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:13:12.167+01:00\">3.13pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Michael Ellis</strong>, a Conservative, goes next.</p> <p><em>Q: You thought the three officers should face disciplinary action for misconduct. But your junior disagreed.</em></p> <p>Yes, says RW.</p> <p><em>Q: You say the officers did not lie, but that they misled. What is the difference?</em></p> <p>RW says the different amounts to intent. If they intended to mislead the press, that would have been gross misconduct. But he does not think that was the case.</p> <p><em>Q: Your report went to the officers before it went to the IPCC. That was illegal, wasn't it?</em></p> <p>RW says he was acting under the directions of the IPCC. But clearly if you look at the regulations that is an irregularity.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-a9564c4b-b0be-4aee-ae8e-8a6da2d76bb6\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382537587094/e1406045-4b36-40df-9104-763969a5cb88-460x276.png\" alt=\"Jerry Reakes-Williams\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Jerry Reakes-Williams Photograph: Parliament TV</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267d7b3e4b0bdde19a2117e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:09:07.705+01:00\">3.09pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong> is asking the questions.</p> <p><em>Q: It is up to the chief constables to submit the final conclusion, isn't it?</em></p> <p>RW says he had a meeting with representatives from the three forces.&nbsp;</p> <p>The IPCC had directed that they were not share their conclusions with the officers.</p> <p>On 31 July a copy of the report, without the conclusions, was sent to the authorities.</p> <p>On the following day he made it clear that there was a difference opinion over the conclusions. The chief constables had the final say. West Mercia and Warwickshire senior officers came back within 24 hours with a recommended conclusion. The IPCC wanted just one conclusion.</p> <p><em>Q: Is Andrew Mitchell owed an apology?</em></p> <p>Yes, says RW.</p> <p><em>Q: Has this had an impact on the reputation of the forces?</em></p> <p>Yes, says RW.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267d781e4b0bdde19a2117d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:05:34.838+01:00\">3.05pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Reakes-Williams (or RW as as will call him from now) confims that the final report did not include his original conclusion that there should be disciplinary action.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267d634e4b0bdde19a2117a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T15:04:01.744+01:00\">3.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Democracy Live is not working, but <a href=\"http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=14006\">the parliamentary website is.</a></p> <p><strong>Jerry Reakes-Williams</strong>, the Professional Standards officer for West Mercia Police, is giving evidence.</p> <p>He wrote the initial report on the conduct of the three Police Federation officers.&nbsp;</p> <p>He says the comments made by the Police Federation representatives did have the effect of misleading the public about that meeting.</p> <p>If he had thought officers had lied, he would have concluded they were guilty of gross misconduct.</p> <p>But misconduct is not the same as gross misconduct, he says.</p> <p>There is room for doubt as to whether Andrew Mitchel gave a &quot;full account&quot;.</p> <p>On the balance of probabilities, he does not think the officers lied, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267d58ce4b0bdde19a21177\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T14:57:55.594+01:00\">2.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The hearing has started, but the live feed is not working. I'm trying a different source now.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267891fe4b027bac8ef99f2\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T14:51:55.097+01:00\">2.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">What the police commissioners have said.</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Last year police and crime commissioners were elected. They were supposed to hold the police to account. But, in relation to this aspect of the &quot;plegbate&quot; affair, at least two of the three police and crime commissioners involved have generally sided with the police.</p> <p><strong>Ron Ball</strong>, the independent Warwickshire police commissioner issued a<a href=\"http://warwickshirepoliceandcrimecommissioner.com/2013/10/15/plebgate-outrage/\"> press notice last Tuesday saying the IPCC's handling of the matter had been &quot;manifestly unfair&quot;. </a>Three days later he put out <a href=\"http://warwickshirepoliceandcrimecommissioner.com/2013/10/18/statement-following-tonights-bbc-newsnight-appearance/\">a statement </a>saying the statement made by the three Police Federation officers was &quot;at best an error of judgment&quot;, but also renewing his criticism of the IPCC. He subsequently accused Andrew Mitchell's friends of <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24627319#TWEET931351\">&quot;baying for blood&quot;.</a></p> <p><strong>Bob Jones,</strong> the Labour West Midlands police commissioner, said <a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/top-officers-had-report-rewritten-to-clear-police-at-heart-of-andrew-mitchell-plebgate-row-8882242.html\">in a statement</a> that the IPCC had led to the three Police Federation officers suffering trial by media.&nbsp;</p> <p>And&nbsp;<strong>Bill Longmore</strong>, the independent West Mercia police and crime commissioner, put&nbsp;out a statement saying <a href=\"http://www.westmercia-pcc.gov.uk/News-and-Events/News-Archive/2013/Bills-response-to-recent-comments-made-by-the-IPCC.aspx\">he was &quot;surprised&quot; that the IPCC has not taken over the investigation into the three officers.</a>&nbsp;He then put out another statement saying <a href=\"http://www.westmercia-pcc.gov.uk/News-and-Events/News-Archive/2013/Bill-is-keen-to-find-out-facts-regarding-comments-made-by-IPCC.aspx\">he was keen to get the facts and would not comment further until after today's hearing.</a></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526787c2e4b027bac8ef99ef\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T14:30:29.757+01:00\">2.30pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Home affairs committee takes evidence on 'plebgate'</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Commons home affairs committee hearing on &quot;plebgate&quot; will be starting soon. Here's the timetable.</p> <p><em>2.45pm:</em> Dame Anne Owers, chair of the Independent Police Complaints Commission, and Deborah Glass, the IPCC's deputy chair, give evidence to the Commons home affairs committee about the “plebgate” controversy. At 3.15pm Chief Inspector Jerry Reakes-Williams, from Professional Standards for Warwickshire and West Mercia Police, gives evidence. At 3.45pm Detective Sergeant Stuart Hinton from Warwickshire Police Federation, Sergeant Chris Jones from West Midlands Police Federation and Inspector Ken MacKaill from West Mercia Police Federation give evidence. And at 4.30pm Chief Constable Andy Parker from Warwickshire Police, Chief Constable David Shaw from West Mercia Police and Chief Constable Chris Sims from West Midlands Police give evidence.</p> <p>I say &quot;plebgate&quot;, but the hearing will not really touch on what Andrew Mitchell did or did not say to the police officers at Downing Street when they refused to open the gates for him as he was leaving on his bicycle last year. That has been investigated by the police, and a file is now with the Crown Prosecution Service which will decide whether officers will be charged. Instead this hearing is just about the conduct of the three Police Federation officers who met Mitchell to discuss the case and who then told journalists that he had refused to give a full account of what happened. West Midlands Police, West Mercia Police and Warwickshire Police decided not to discipline them. But the IPCC criticised this decision on the grounds that an investigation seemed to show that they had not told the truth about what Mitchell said.</p> <p>It was a small incident, involving four people. But what the Police Federation officers said that day helped to contribute to Mitchell's decision to resign as chief whip and it has become a story about whether police officers can be trusted, whether the Police Federation behaves responsibly and whether it is right for the police to investigate misconduct allegations against officers itself. (In other circles this is called &quot;marking your own homework&quot;. As we in the press have discovered, this has rather gone out of fashion.)</p> <p>Here is some background reading before the hearing starts.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.ipcc.gov.uk/news/ipcc-disagrees-findings-west-mercia-investigation-conduct-police-federation-representatives\">• The press statement from Deborah Glass, the Independent Police Complaints Commission deputy chair, last week criticising West Mercia Police for not taking disciplinary action against the three officers and calling for that decision to be reconsidered.</a>&nbsp;Here's an extract.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The investigation by West Mercia Police concluded that although the Police Federation undoubtedly contributed to the pressure on Mr Mitchell and his decision to resign, none of the officers had a case to answer for misconduct or gross misconduct. The investigating officer concluded that while the federation representatives' comments to the media could be viewed as ambiguous or misleading, there was no deliberate intention to lie.</p> <p>I disagree. In my view, the evidence is such that a panel should determine whether the three officers gave a false account of the meeting in a deliberate attempt to support their MPS colleague and discredit Mr Mitchell, in pursuit of a wider agenda. In my opinion the evidence indicates an issue of honesty and integrity, not merely na&iuml;ve or poor professional judgment.</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.ipcc.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/investigation_commissioner_reports/West%20Mercia%20Investigation.pdf\">• The full six-page statement from Glass setting out her case in more detail (pdf).</a>&nbsp;This give more details of what happened when Mitchell met the three officers, and why their account of it afterwards was misleading.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It is clear from the recording that at the start of the meeting Mr Mitchell makes his apology, and hopes he can “draw a line” under the incident. He answers the question of “what he did say”:&nbsp;“The incident was very brief I complied with the officer and I picked up my bicycle but I did say under my breath but audibly, in frustration, I thought you lot were supposed to f***ing help us and it is for that I apologise and I am grateful to that officer for accepting my apology and I should never have said it and I will never do it again...” ...</p> <p>Immediately after the meeting the West Mercia officer, who did not speak during the meeting, is the principal spokesman when the officers speak to the waiting media ....&nbsp;When asked by a reporter if Mr Mitchell should resign he says:&nbsp;“I think Mr Mitchell now has no option but to resign, he’s continuing to refuse to elaborate on what happened, I think his position is untenable.”&nbsp;</p> <p>Immediately following this interview all three officers gave separate interviews along similar lines to various media.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.ipcc.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/investigation_commissioner_reports/Transcript%20of%20meeting.pdf\">• The transcript of Mitchell's 45-minute meeting with the three officers on 12 October 2012.</a></p> <p><a href=\"http://www.westmercia.police.uk/news/news-articles/statement-from-warwickshire-west-mercia-and-west-midlands-police.html?utm_medium=twitter&amp;utm_source=twitterfeed\">• A joint statement from Warwickshire, West Midlands and West Mercia police responding to the IPCC statement.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Despite a thorough investigation under the supervision of the IPCC we do not believe that there is sufficient evidence to support the view that the officers concerned should face misconduct proceedings. Our view is that the officers have demonstrated poor judgement in arranging and attending the meeting in the first place. In light of this our position is that management action is a proportionate response.</p> <p>It is important to emphasise these points;</p> <p>i) Mr Mitchell has not made a complaint against police;</p> <p>ii) Had the IPCC decided at any stage during the investigation to treat this as a managed or an independent investigation they had the power to direct the forces to convene misconduct proceedings. They have chosen not to exercise these powers despite being invited to reconsider and reminded of their options as recently as last week.</p> <p>iii) At any stage during a supervised investigation the IPCC can direct further work to be done and they have not done so in this case.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.polfed.org/newsroom/1655.aspx\">• The Police Federation's initial response to the IPCC statement.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The Police Federation of England and Wales welcome the conclusions of the IPCC-supervised investigation into the actions of three Police Federation representatives, which found no evidence of misconduct. The IPCC had the choice at the outset of this investigation either to conduct an independent, managed or supervised investigation, and it chose to supervise. The investigation team has reached its conclusion and in accordance with statutory regulations, a decision has been made by the appropriate authority that there is no case to answer.&nbsp;</p> <p>Against this factual background, we are therefore shocked that the IPCC Commissioner, Deborah Glass, would then appoint herself judge and jury by releasing her personal view that she disagrees with the findings and asks the public to decide. This is done with the full knowledge that her status and title will naturally undermine the considered findings of the investigation in the eyes of the public, whereas in fact those investigating and deciding the case are the proper arbiters in this matter.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24615491\">• An account of the partial apology that the three Police Federation officers issued on Monday.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We acknowledge the investigation's criticism relating to our poor judgement in talking to the media following the meeting with Andrew Mitchell, for which we take this opportunity to apologise.</p> <p>We would like to emphasise (as we did to the investigation) that in no way did any of us ever plan or intend to mislead anyone about what occurred during this meeting or otherwise.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267cc4de4b027bac8ef9a27\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T14:18:47.767+01:00\">2.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here are the main points from the urgent question on Grangemouth. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/chinese-banking-fears-markets-minutes-greece-live#block-5267c066e4b0c53fe22c1f08\">I have taken it from Graeme Wearden's business live blog. </a>Graeme has been covering the Grangemouth story in great detail.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>• <strong>The UK government hopes that the Grangemouth petrochemical plant can still be saved, despite its owner Ineos announcing plans today to shut it down.&nbsp;</strong></p> <p>Energy and climate change secretary Ed Davey told MPs repeatedly that the government wants the <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/chinese-banking-fears-markets-minutes-greece-live#block-5267b483e4b0bdde19a21151\">plant to stay open if at all possible</a>. </strong>It would&nbsp;still consider a business case to provide investment to help keep the plant running.&nbsp;</p> <p>Davey also confirmed that detailed contingency plans have been drawn up to protect firms and customers from running out of fuel and chemical supplies.</p> <p>He will meet with MPs at 4.15pm to discuss the issue in more detail.&nbsp;</p> <p>• <strong>Many MPs are very worried about the impact on the Scottish economy, and the knock-on effects on the UK chemicals industry.</strong></p> <p><strong>Michael Moore, Liberal Democrat MP,</strong> called it &quot;An&nbsp;act of industrial vandalism not seen in decades&quot;.</p> <p>• <strong>MPs were critical of both Ineos and the unions, for allowing the dispute to reach this point.</strong></p> <p>Alistair Darling, former chancellor, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/chinese-banking-fears-markets-minutes-greece-live#block-5267b732e4b027bac8ef9a18\"><strong>said</strong></a> it would be tragic to lose the plant to an industrial dispute reminiscent of the 1970s, while Sir Malcolm Bruce said both sides were guilty of &quot;a degree of intransigence&quot;. Tom Watson MP called for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/chinese-banking-fears-markets-minutes-greece-live#block-5267ba6de4b027bac8ef9a19\"><strong>an independent assessment of Grangemouth's finances</strong></a>.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267bdc5e4b0bdde19a2115e\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T14:03:55.101+01:00\">2.03pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Lunchtime summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/energy-industry-competition-test-cameron\"><strong>•&nbsp;</strong></a><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/energy-industry-competition-test-cameron\">David Cameron has announced a review of green energy taxes after saying they had helped push up household bills to &quot;unacceptable&quot; levels</a>.</strong>&nbsp;He made the announcement at PMQs, after Ed Miliband challenged him to say if he agreed with Sir John Major and Labour about the need to recoup money from the energy companies. (See<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/23/mps-question-police-over-plebgate-politics-live-blog#block-5267b51ae4b0bdde19a21154\"> 1.08pm</a> and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/23/mps-question-police-over-plebgate-politics-live-blog#block-5267c3e0e4b027bac8ef9a21\">1.44pm.)</a>&nbsp;The Conservative MP Zac Goldsmith, a strong environmentalist, took to Twitter to criticise Cameron for going back on green pledges he made before 2010.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/ZacGoldsmith/statuses/392972825671516160\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>In 2010, leaders fought to prove they were the greenest. 3 yrs on, they're desperately blaming their own policies on the other. Muppets.</p>— Zac Goldsmith (@ZacGoldsmith) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ZacGoldsmith/statuses/392972825671516160\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p><strong>• John Bercow, the Commons speaker, has rebuked Cameron for calling Miliband a &quot;conman&quot;. Bercow made the point in an intervention during PMQs.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Let me just say, I let it go the first time, the word 'conman' is frankly unparliamentary. The prime minister is a man of great versatility in the use of language - it's a bit below the level. We'll leave it there, it's a bit below the level.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/ineos-closes-grangemouth-petrochemicals-plant\">• Ineos has announced it is closing the</a></strong><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/ineos-closes-grangemouth-petrochemicals-plant\">&nbsp;petrochemical plant at Grangemouth&nbsp;following a bitter row over pay and conditions</a></strong><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/ineos-closes-grangemouth-petrochemicals-plant\">, putting 800 workers' jobs at risk.</a></strong>&nbsp;My colleague Graeme Wearden has more details&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/23/chinese-banking-fears-markets-minutes-greece-live\">on the business live blog.</a></p> <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/23/plebgate-david-davis-royal-commission-police-ethics\">• David Davis, an ally of Andrew Mitchell, has </a></strong><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/23/plebgate-david-davis-royal-commission-police-ethics\">has called for a royal commission to investigate the &quot;crisis of ethics&quot; in the&nbsp;police,&nbsp;as three chief constables prepare for questioning by a committee of MPs over issues raised by the Plebgate affair</a>.</strong>&nbsp;As Rowena Mason reports,&nbsp;Davis said police should wear microphones and cameras to record their actions to address a decline in public trust – an idea that has won the support of Nick Herbert, a former policing minister, who said the idea was &quot;worth piloting&quot;.&nbsp;The call came as Sir&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/bernard-hogan-howe\">Bernard Hogan-Howe</a>, Britain's most senior officer, admitted the Plebgate row had clouded the public view of Scotland Yard and had taken too long to deal with.<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/23/plebgate-scotland-yard-police-commissioner-andrew-mitchell\">Speaking on LBC on Wednesday,&nbsp;</a>he said: &quot;During the time this thing has been an issue, the Met has been performing better than ever. We've just got to live with the reality - the newspaper headlines, the fact that you're talking about it, clouds the fact that crime's coming down at its fastest for 30 years.</p> <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/oct/23/effect-benefit-cap-work-pensions-welfare-official-figures?CMP=twt_fd\">• Mike Penning, a welfare minister, has&nbsp;admitted that the government does not know how many people the benefit cap is forcing into work, after&nbsp;a new study said the flagship welfare policy was not helping the unemployed or saving money.</a></strong></p> <p><strong><a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-measures-to-help-hard-working-families-with-the-cost-of-driving\">• The Ministry of Justice has announced plans to help control the cost of motoring, including &quot;a crackdown on whiplash fraud, a freeze on MOT test prices and a scheme designed to reduce the cost of fuel at motorway service stations&quot;.</a></strong></p> <p><strong><a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/news/invest-more-to-ensure-economy-hits-top-gear-danny-alexander-to-tell-businesses\">• Danny Alexander, the chief secretary to the Treasury, has said that British businesses should do their bit to revive the economy by investing some of the &pound;500bn they have in their reserves.</a>&nbsp;</strong>Here's an excerpt from a press notice about a speech he is giving tonight.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>He will call on business leaders to invest some of their &pound;500 billion cash balances - enough for 50 Olympic games - now to ensure the economy hits ‘top gear’.</p> <p>Had businesses increased their investment by just 10% in 2012, he will say, then the level of GDP would be &pound;12bn higher - almost a whole percentage point growth in GDP ...</p> <p>Cash balances in non-financial businesses have risen by &pound;14 billion in the last quarter and &pound;104 billion since pre crisis levels - a 26% increase since the financial crisis. Cash balances now stand at over &pound;500 billion.</p> <p>At the same time business investment is currently 25% below its pre-recession peak.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/23/government-individual-voter-register-2015-election\">•&nbsp;Government plans to go ahead with the next election on the basis of an individual voter register, as opposed to the current household register, have been given a boost after an experiment suggested nearly 80% of the electorate could be transferred to an individual register automatically.</a></strong></p> <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/wellbeing/measuring-national-well-being/personal-well-being-across-the-uk--2012-13/sb---personal-well-being-across-the-uk--2012-13.html\">• The Office for National Statistics has published figures showing that happiness increased between 2011-12 and 2012-13.</a></strong></p> <p><strong>• Justine Greening, the international development secretary, has announced&nbsp;Britain is to provide a further &pound;2m in aid to provide water, sanitation and protection to vulnerable Syrian children who have fled to Iraq to escape their country's civil war.&nbsp;</strong></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267c3e0e4b027bac8ef9a21\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T13:44:31.045+01:00\">1.44pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here is more about energy initiatives announced (or half-announced - see <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/23/mps-question-police-over-plebgate-politics-live-blog#block-5267b51ae4b0bdde19a21154\">1.08pm)</a> by David Cameron at PMQs. This is from the Press Association.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Downing Street said that details of the competition review will be set out next week in the annual energy statement to the House of Commons by energy secretary Ed Davey. </p> <p>An annual review of competition in the energy sector will be conducted by regulator Ofgem, the Office of Fair Trading and the new Competition and Markets Authority. The first review is expected to begin within weeks and report next year, said the prime minister's official spokesman. </p> <p>It will look at issues affecting competition and consumers, ranging from prices and profit levels to barriers to new entrants in the market, as well as how companies engage with customers. </p> <p>&quot;With regard to the charges that are part of people's bills, we are of course looking across the board at what more government can do to help customers and consumers,&quot; said the spokesman. </p> <p>The spokesman declined to give any detail of sanctions which energy companies might face as a result, but said: &quot;It would be wrong at this stage to rule anything out in terms of how we get more competition into the market.&quot; </p> <p>The spokesman said the review was agreed by both Conservative and Liberal Democrat sides of the coalition and insisted that the Government was not giving up its claim to be &quot;the greenest ever&quot;. </p> <p>The prime minister's ambition to &quot;roll back&quot; green levies has also been discussed with Liberal Democrats over recent weeks, and details will be released in Chancellor George Osborne's autumn statement on December 4. </p> <p>Downing Street sources said that, if there was no policy change, green levies could rise from the current &pound;112 to &pound;194 - or 14% of the typical household bill - by 2020. Cameron wants action to reduce the impact of the levies, the source said.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p>And here is what Labour are saying. This is from a party source.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The prime minister is clearly in a panic over energy prices. He is refusing to take real action to tackle overcharging now. He wants to wait another year when bills are going up 10% as we speak. The Labour party has a comprehensive plan to freeze prices and reset the market. David Cameron's response is panicked and totally inadequate.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267bef3e4b027bac8ef9a1b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T13:23:59.736+01:00\">1.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>My colleague Patrick Wintour has a shrewd point about David Cameron's comment about &quot;green&quot; levies.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/patrickwintour/statuses/392986372295761920\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Day after Sir John Major warns poor face choice between eating &amp; heating, Cameron says he'll roll back green levies, half of which help poor</p>— Patrick Wintour (@patrickwintour) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/patrickwintour/statuses/392986372295761920\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>I put &quot;green&quot; in inverted commas because some of the measures Cameron was referring to, such as the <a href=\"https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/environmental-programmes/energy-companies-obligation-eco\">Energy Companies Obligation,</a> involve funding energy saving measures for the poor. You could see them as much as welfare measures as climate change measures.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b51ae4b0bdde19a21154\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T13:08:30.651+01:00\">1.08pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">PMQs - Verdict</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>PMQ's - Verdict:</strong> Earlier I said that was a clear win for Ed Miliband. Half an hour later, it looks even more significant - a big win, that left David Cameron. Wit does not always trump bluster, but it did today. Miliband's opening question was very neat.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The prime miniser said that anyone who wanted to intervene in energy markets was living in a Marxist universe. Can he tell the House how does he feel now that the red peril has claimed Sir John Major?</p> </blockquote> <p>And Miliband continue to mock Cameron effectively, particularly with his question about someone taking Cameron's advice to switch from British Gas only to be hit with a price increase from npower. Cameron's front-foot aggression seemed misplaced, and his final jibe, about Major being a &quot;good man&quot; and Miliband being a &quot;con man&quot;, was marked by a touch of desperation (although it was also noticeable that he was not going on about Miliband being &quot;weak&quot; as much as usual).</p> <p>However, tone is not particularly relevant. At PMQs even the best debating skills cannot disguise a policy lacuna, and Cameron's real problem was that he did not have an effective response to Miliband's best question: Major proposes recovering money from energy companies via a windfall tax, Labour propose using a price freeze, so how would you recoup that money? Cameron does not have a full answer yet, and that's why he lost.</p> <p>But Cameron did have half an answer. In fact, he made three significant concessions on energy policy.</p> <p><strong>• He said that energy bills had reached a &quot;completely unacceptable level&quot;</strong>. I don't think he has ever said this so bluntly before. This represents a victory for Miliband,who has forced him into this position.</p> <p><strong>• Cameron was clearly than he has every been before about wanting to get rid of the green levies that, according to Cameron, add more than &pound;100 to fuel bills.</strong> &quot;We need to roll back some of the green regulation and charges on our bills,&quot; he said.</p> <p><strong>• He said he would apply a &quot;proper competition test&quot; to the energy market.</strong></p> <p>If Cameron had adopted an air of contrition, and flagged these up as significant concessions, he might have been able to wrong-foot Miliband. As it was, they were rather buried beneath his bluster. But these announcements mark the start of a Conservative fight-back on this agenda, and we are bound to hear more about them in the coming weeks.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T13:14:46.297+01:00\">at 1.14pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b499e4b0bdde19a21152\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:37:20.313+01:00\">12.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here is some more on what Cameron was saying about green levies on fuel bills.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/bbcnickrobinson/statuses/392974366163890176\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Sources say that the review of green taxes and regulations will be spelt out in the Autumn statement</p>— Nick Robinson (@bbcnickrobinson) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bbcnickrobinson/statuses/392974366163890176\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>And here's is a bit more on the competition test Cameron mentioned.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/ToryTreasury/statuses/392974127247933441\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/patrickwintour\">@patrickwintour</a> new annual competition test will involve OFT and new CMA (replacing Competition Commission)</p>— Tory Treasury (@ToryTreasury) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ToryTreasury/statuses/392974127247933441\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b3a7e4b0bdde19a2114f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:34:14.420+01:00\">12.34pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <strong>Kevin Barron</strong> says he wrote to Cameron about Lynton Crosby's involvement in public house. Four previous prime ministers would have replied to his letters. Why won't Cameron?</p> <p>Cameron says public health is the responsibility of the public health minister. Crosby's responsibility is the destruction of the Labour party. He is doing a pretty good job.</p> <p>And that's it. PMQs is over.</p> <p>Ed Davey is now replying to an urgent question about Grangemouth.</p> <p>I will post a full PMQs verdict shortly.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b34de4b0bdde19a2114e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:31:46.503+01:00\">12.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's<strong> Diana Johnson</strong> asks if it is fair that a sacked pregnant woman will have to pay &pound;1,200 to take a case to an employment tribunal.</p> <p>Cameron says it is right that people have employment rights. But they should have to work for a firm for a period before they qualify, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b2f9e4b0bdde19a2114d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:29:58.689+01:00\">12.29pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Andy Sawford,</strong> the Labour MP, asks Cameron if he say the Channel 4 report on the reality of working life in Britain today.</p> <p>Cameron says the proportion of people on zero-hours contract was the same in 2012 as it was in 2000.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b2b5e4b027bac8ef9a17\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:28:51.312+01:00\">12.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Julian Smith</strong>, a Conservative, asks Cameron to pay tribute to people working in the intelligence services following the Guardian's &quot;reckless&quot; intelligence leaks.</p> <p>Cameron says people in the intelligence services do not get the credit they deserve. &quot;We cannot praise these people too highly&quot;.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b20ce4b0bdde19a2114b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:27:18.220+01:00\">12.27pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>George Howarth</strong>, a Labour MP, asks if government support to local government should be related to need. He says households in his area have lost &pound;40 over the last two years, while in Cameron's constituency they have gained &pound;6.</p> <p>Cameron says that if you look at spending per household, grant plus council tax, in Liverpool the figure is &pound;3,122, while in his constituency the figure is less than &pound;2,000.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b1d4e4b027bac8ef9a16\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:24:42.786+01:00\">12.24pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Nadine Dorries,</strong> a Conservative, asks about a free school application in her constituency.</p> <p>Cameron says he wants to put &quot;rocket boosters&quot; under the free schools policy.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b1a4e4b027bac8ef9a15\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:23:55.409+01:00\">12.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <strong>Tom Watson</strong> says fixed-odd betting machines turn bookmakers into casinos. Will Cameron ban them?</p> <p>Cameron says it is worth having a look at this issue.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b16ce4b027bac8ef9a14\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:23:13.674+01:00\">12.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Crispin Blunt</strong>, a Conservative, asks about Osborne Constuction, a firm in his constituency.</p> <p>Cameron says he is glad to hear it is doing well. Osborne Consruction is also doing well all over the country.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b129e4b027bac8ef9a13\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:22:18.054+01:00\">12.22pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Yvonne Fovargue</strong>, a Labour MP, asks what's fair about the bedroom tax.</p> <p>Cameron says Labour have opposed every welfare reduction proposed by the government. They would have to find &pound;85bn to fund this, he says.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b101e4b0bdde19a2114a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:21:05.858+01:00\">12.21pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Cameron says the government wants an open energy maket. And Ed Miliband appointed five of the nine people of Ofgem. If the energy market doesn't work, it is Miliband's fault, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b0d5e4b027bac8ef9a12\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:20:13.950+01:00\">12.20pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <strong>Meg Hillier</strong> asks Cameron to abandon the welfare cap. Cameron says Labour are the welfare party.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b061e4b027bac8ef9a11\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:19:46.264+01:00\">12.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Richard Benyon</strong><strong>, a</strong> Conservative, says more than 300,000 new businesses have been registered over the last three years. Cutting regulations helps them. What more can the government do?</p> <p>Cameron says news out today shows there are more companies than have ever existed. Some 400,000 businesses have been created under this government, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267b02ee4b0bdde19a21148\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:17:47.735+01:00\">12.17pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>John Bercow</strong> says the word &quot;con man&quot; is unparliamentary. He let it go first time, he says, but Cameron should know it is &quot;a bit below the level&quot;. Cameron, a man of great versatility, should use another phrase, he suggests.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267affbe4b0bdde19a21147\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:16:54.415+01:00\">12.16pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Brian Binley</strong>, a Conservative, asks Cameron to reduce the impact of Chris Huhne's renewable energy measures.</p> <p>Cameron says Binley has a point. Green measures are adding &pound;112 to bills.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267af99e4b0bdde19a21146\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:16:08.337+01:00\">12.16pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <strong>Jim Dobbin</strong> says 1.5m people in the UK are addicted to drugs like diazepam. They are victims of repeat prescriptions, he says.</p> <p>Cameron says Dobbin is right to highlight this issue. People who are not addicts have become hooked on these drugs.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267af1de4b027bac8ef9a10\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:14:20.173+01:00\">12.14pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Snap PMQs Verdict:</strong> Clear victory for Miliband (or for Miliband and John Major, to give credit where it is due). Cameron is shifting his stance on energy, now saying clearly that the price rises are unacceptable, but he did not have a good answer to Miliband. More later ...&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ae9be4b027bac8ef9a0f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:12:22.659+01:00\">12.12pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Mililband said telling people to switch suppliers was a con. What would he say to someone who switched from British Gas to npower, only to see npower raise its prices.</p> <p>Cameron says Miliband left the energy market in a mess. Miliband is trying to con the public. The government will deliver for people.</p> <p>Miliband says John Major was right. Cameron is not standing up to the energy companies. The price rises will affect people who Cameron will never meet and whose lives he does not understand.</p> <p>Cameron says Major is a good man. Miliband is a con man.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267adcde4b0bdde19a21143\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:10:14.465+01:00\">12.10pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Miliband says Cameron is changing his policies every week. Ed Davey said green measures had nothing to do with price rises. And Cameron used to say vote blue, go green.</p> <p>Cameron says Miliband created the big six energy companies. He says he has Labour's briefing on its energy policies. Question 7 is: What would stop the energy companies increasing their prices in advance? There is no answer, Cameron says. And question 6 asks: What is to stop the companies putting their prices up after the freeze. The document says the public would take a dim view.</p> <p>Miliband says energy bills went down by &pound;100 when he was energy secretary. Cameron says the price rises are unacceptable. But he is the prime minister, heaven help us. So he should implement Labour's policy now. Two parties working together in the common interest. Cameron tries to rise, but Miliband gets him to sit down. Let's do it now, Miliband says.</p> <p>Cameron says Labour's policy is price con. Prices would go up before and afterwards. It is a cynical ploy, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267acdfe4b0bdde19a21142\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:06:47.317+01:00\">12.06pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Ed Miliband</strong> pays his own tribute to the dead soldier.</p> <p>Cameron said anyone intervening in the energy markets was living in a Marxist universe. How does he feel now that the red peril has claimed John Major, Miliband asks.</p> <p>Cameron says he believes in intervening in the energy market. Bills have reached an unacceptable level. We have to have a conversation about what puts them up. Miliband is engaged in cynical gimmicks.</p> <p>Miliband says Major won a majority, unlike Major. Cameron now says the price increases are &quot;unacceptable&quot;. So what are we going to do? Major wants a windfall tax. Miliband wants a price freeze. What would Cameron do?</p> <p>Cameron says he wants to roll back some of the green regulations and charges. We know who put them in place? John Major did won an election. He beat a weak and incredible Labour leader. Isn't that familiar? And he said Labour's policy was unworkable. There are four bits of a bill: wholesale prices; transmission costs; profits; and green measures. Cameron says there will be a proper competition test for the market.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ac7fe4b027bac8ef9a0d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:02:51.948+01:00\">12.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Julian Brazier</strong>, a Conservative, asks if it is a good time for those branches of the Police Federation that traduced Andrew Mitchell, and from Ed Miliband.</p> <p>Cameron says he wants to start by paying tribute to the police. But the police do need to make a &quot;proper apology&quot; to Mitchell. We all need to consider what we said at the time, he says, and he hopes Ed Miliband will consider this.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267ac47e4b0bdde19a21140\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T12:01:14.981+01:00\">12.01pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>David Cameron</strong> starts by paying tribute to a soldier killed in Afghanistan. He made the ultimate sacrifice, Cameron says.</p> <p>And he says, on a happier note, MPs will join him in celebrating the christening of baby Prince George.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267aa15e4b027bac8ef9a0b\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T11:51:39.943+01:00\">11.51am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">David Cameron at PMQs</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>We've got PMQs in 10 minutes.&nbsp;</p> <p>Grangemouth and John Major are likely to be the key topics.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267a4a9e4b027bac8ef9a0a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T11:28:46.980+01:00\">11.28am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here's what Number 10 are saying about the Grangemouth closure.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392958694339923968\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>No 10 will not bail out <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23grangemouth&amp;src=hash\">#grangemouth</a></p>— norman smith (@BBCNormanS) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392958694339923968\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392958968223789056\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>No 10 say ready to help with discuSions over <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23grangemouth&amp;src=hash\">#grangemouth</a> but up to unions and management to resolve dispute</p>— norman smith (@BBCNormanS) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392958968223789056\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392959078248742912\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>No threat to fuel supplies from <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23grangemouth&amp;src=hash\">#grangemouth</a> closure say No 10</p>— norman smith (@BBCNormanS) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392959078248742912\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267a005e4b027bac8ef9a06\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T11:08:22.758+01:00\">11.08am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>There will be an urgent question on the Grangemouth closure in the Commons at 12.30pm, Sky News is reporting.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267962de4b0bdde19a21134\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T10:48:09.704+01:00\">10.48am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>You can read all today's Guardian politics stories&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/all\">here.</a>&nbsp;And all the politics stories filed yesterday, including some in today's papers, are<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/22/all\">&nbsp;here.</a></p> <p>As for the rest of the papers, here's&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.politicshome.com/uk/todays_must_reads.html\">the PoliticsHome list of top 10 must reads,</a>&nbsp;here's&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.conservativehome.com/frontpage/2013/10/newslinks-for-wednesday-23rd-october-2013.html\">the ConservativeHome round-up of today's politics stories in the papers&nbsp;</a>and here's&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/staggers/2013/10/morning-call-pick-papers-18\">the New Statesman's list of top 10 comment articles.</a></p> <p>And here are five articles that I found particularly interesting.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/columnists/article3901699.ece\">• David Davis in an article in the Times (paywall) says that the Independent Police Complaints Commission should be given more powers and that there should be a royal commission on policing.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>What we need is not a new regulator, but a tougher regulator. Earlier this year a parliamentary inquiry concluded that the Independent Police Complaints Commission “has neither the powers nor the resources that it needs to get to the truth when the integrity of the police is in doubt”. The Government should respond by giving the IPCC the powers and resources to outrank and overrule every chief of police in the land — to become a British “Untouchables”. Never again should a police force be able to delay or frustrate an IPCC investigation.</p> <p>However, while a tougher IPCC would ensure rigorous investigation of police misconduct, identifying such misdemeanours after the event is not enough. Nor is this a problem that can be solved by the Government’s recent Winsor-inspired reforms. The issues are bigger than pay, paperwork and pensions. This is a crisis of ethics.</p> <p>Britain needs root-and-branch reform of policing culture, a feat beyond the powers of even a powerful independent regulator. The Government should appoint a Royal Commission to investigate the conduct of the police. The lessons about what behaviour is expected from a British police officer should be instilled from Day 1.</p> </blockquote> <p>He also says officers should wear cameras and microphones to record their dealings with members of the public.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The police put millions of innocent people under surveillance in order to catch a tiny minority of wrongdoers. Perhaps now it is time to make officers wear a camera and microphone while on duty. When they tried this in California, use of force by police officers dropped by two thirds in a year. This technology could also help to defend police officers who have vexatious claims made against them.</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/778b78ee-3b25-11e3-a7ec-00144feab7de.html#ixzz2iXHzDb6K\">• Jim Pickard and Elizabeth Rigby in the Financial Times (subscription) say Ed Miliband has told supporters at a private dinner that he anticipates a &quot;big fight&quot; with Fleet Street.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Ed Miliband has put Labour on notice for a “big fight” with Fleet Street ahead of the general election, telling supporters that the newspapers are “less powerful now than they were”.</p> <p>The Labour leader, speaking at a private dinner for Labour donors, said the days in which newspapers and the news media could attack his party “without response” were over ...</p> <p>Recorded at a dinner at the Phoenix Palace, a luxury Chinese restaurant in Marylebone, the Labour leader said [his row with the Daily Mail about his father] was an emblem of how politics was conducted in Britain.</p> <p>“We’ve got to be willing to call these people out,” he said. “They are less powerful than people ever thought and they are less powerful now than they were.”</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/columnists/danielfinkelstein/article3901669.ece\">• Daniel Finkelstein in the Times (paywall) says voters will not believe Ed Miliband when he says he can freeze energy bills.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>When I worked for William Hague back in the late 1990s, we were experimenting with focus group research for the first time. None of us quite appreciated how it worked. We would discover that groups strongly agreed with us on an issue — tax allowances, for instance — and we would try playing back the policy to those voters in the form of a promise.</p> <p>Yet the moment these same voters heard their own favoured policy read back to them by a politician they started to disagree with it.</p> <p>“That will never work,” they would say. Or: “That sounds fine, but they’ll never do it.” Or: “Yeah, but how are they going to pay for it?”</p> <p>They are also much more likely to believe that a politician might bring to an end something they approve of than that they will deliver something nice. This is one of the reasons, I am afraid, that negative campaigning is effective despite most people saying that they don’t like negative campaigns.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2472311/Fuel-prices-advertised-signs-motorway-help-drivers-avoid-ripped-off.html#ixzz2iXKhJgAG%20\">• James Slack in the Daily Mail says the government is introducing a range of measures to cut the cost of motoring.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Electronic signs are to be put up on motorways to expose service stations trying to rip off motorists with inflated charges.</p> <p>They are part of a package of measures unveiled by Justice Secretary Chris Grayling today to reduce the cost of motoring.</p> <p>They include freezing the MoT test fee for a car at &pound;54.85 until 2015, and a review of the cost of taking a driving test and applying for a provisional licence.</p> </blockquote> <p>Grayling is involved because his department is taking steps to cut the number of fraudulent whiplash claims which drive insurance costs up.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/news/10397946/Turn-off-parking-meters-and-save-the-high-street-minister-tells-councils.html\">• Brandon Lewis, the communities minister, tells the Daily Telegraph in an interview that councils should lift charges for parking.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Brandon Lewis, the high streets minister, called on local authority bosses to risk legal challenges by offering motorists free short-stay parking.</p> <p>In his first interview since taking on the high streets role in this month’s reshuffle, Mr Lewis said that councils must make high streets an “attractive place where people want to go” by not enforcing punishing parking charges.</p> <p>He also called for a change in the role played by parking wardens across the country, insisting that they are not there to “penalise” drivers.</p> <p>“If we want to see our high streets and our market towns prosper and do well we’ve got to make it easy and affordable to park,” he said. </p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267957ee4b027bac8ef99fa\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T10:24:51.518+01:00\">10.24am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Ineos has announced that it is going to close part of the Grangemouth petrochemical plant in Scotland. The Press Association has just filed this.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Part of the giant Grangemouth site is to close following a bitter row over pay and conditions.</p> <p>Owner Ineos has decided to shut down the petrochemical side of the complex, which is situated next to the firm's oil refinery. </p> <p>Workers were given the grim news at a meeting with Ineos chairman Calum MacLean. </p> <p>The news follows the passing of a deadline on a survival plan put to employees which asked them to accept changes to pensions and other terms and conditions. </p> <p>The Unite union said around 680 of the site's 1,370-strong workforce had rejected the company's proposals, which include a pay freeze for 2014-16, removal of a bonus up to 2016, a reduced shiftallowance and ending of the final salary pension scheme.&nbsp;</p> <p>Ineos said owner Jim Ratcliffe and other shareholders met yesterday to study the response from the workforce to their survival plan, and wanted the employees to be the first to know of any decision the company makes.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-248cc6de-d7ff-4a81-9477-bd04cde16a8a\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382520277093/6807d9ac-ec0b-48e4-850e-d598980b586c-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Grangemouth oil refinery in Falkirk, Scotland.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Grangemouth oil refinery in Falkirk, Scotland. Photograph: David Cheskin/PA</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267936ae4b027bac8ef99f7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T10:20:05.841+01:00\">10.20am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>It is not just <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/23/plebgate-david-davis-surveillance-police\">David Davis saying the police should wear cameras and microphones to record their contact with members of the public .</a> <strong>Roger Evans,</strong> a Conservative member of the London assembly, has sent out a news release saying he will be asking Boris Johnson to pilot the idea in the capital.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Think of the role video cameras in patrol vehicles have played in helping ensure the safety of police and public, the next logical step is to extend these camera’s to the police officers person. Though this sounds like very futuristic kit, these wearable cameras are quite cheap and easy to use, and it’s not uncommon to see something like these police worn cameras in a local electronics shop. Staffordshire police have been equipping officers with this technology since 2010 and they not only help reduce bureaucracy as officers can avoid writing long statements, they have reduced complaints against officers significantly. Body Worn Cameras will represent great value for money to the Met, so let’s get moving with a full out trial of this tech.</p> </blockquote> <p>According to Evans, in Staffordshire the use of body cameras of this kind has cut the time taken to file incident reports by 22%, given officers an extra 50 minutes of patrol time per day and led to a reduction in disorder and anti-social behaviour. He says that there have been no complaints against officers wearing the cameras and that Staffordshire Police are now buying 530 of them.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52679035e4b0bdde19a2112d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T10:09:29.202+01:00\">10.09am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>According to the Office for National Statistics, we got happier last year. Only a bit, mind you, but I suppose that's better than getting less happy. The ONS has published <a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171778_328486.pdf\">its personal well-being data for 2012-13 (pdf), </a>and here are the key points from the summary.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>• Personal well-being improved in the UK between 2011/12 and 2012/13. Ratings for life satisfaction and feeling that the things we do in life are worthwhile increased on average, whilst anxiety levels fell.</p> <p>• The proportions rating their personal well-being as very high or very low fell between 2011/12 and 2012/13 in the UK, while the proportion rating their well-being around 7 or 8 out of 10 increased.•&nbsp;Among the countries of the UK, Northern Ireland had the highest average ratings for life satisfaction, worthwhile and happiness in 2012/13. A greater proportion of people in Northern Ireland rated their life satisfaction, worthwhile and happiness as very high (9 or 10 out of 10) than in any other country.</p> <p>• Among the English regions, the South West and the South East had some of the highest levels of average life satisfaction and worthwhile ratings in 2012/13. The South West also had proportionately more people than any other region rating life satisfaction, worthwhile and happiness as 9 or 10 out of 10</p> </blockquote> <p>Why did people get happier? The ONS says it is not entirely sure. But the Olympics and the Diamond Jubilee may have been a factor.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Reasons for the small improvement in personal well-being between 2011/12 and 2012/13 are not fully understood.</p> <p>Recent ONS analysis on ‘What matters most to personal well-being?’ (ONS, 2013b) found that the factors most associated with personal well-being are health, employment situation and relationship status. Where possible, these factors will be referred to to help contextualise differences in personal well-being across different areas of the UK.</p> <p>At the UK level, improvements in the labour market picture and special events such as the Queen’s Diamond Jubilee and the 2012 Summer Olympic and Paralympic games were suggested as factors which could have positively influenced people’s assessment of their personal well-being during the 2012/13 period (ONS, 2013a).&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52678c3be4b027bac8ef99f4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T09:47:38.540+01:00\">9.47am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Another Conservative MP has had a go at Ron Ball, the Warwickshire police commissioner who complained that <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24627319#TWEET931351\">Andrew Mitchell's friends were &quot;baying for blood&quot; over &quot;plebgate&quot;.</a> This is what <strong>David Ruffley</strong> told BBC News.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>[We're] certainly not [baying for blood]. We have the three chief constables in today and they investigated themselves, they said at the end of the day no disciplinary proceedings, but there is evidence they changed the story from being disciplinary proceedings recommended to no charge to answer. So first of all we need to know what was changed.</p> </blockquote> <p>Ruffley also said today's hearing would expose the &quot;inadequacy&quot; of the system that allows the police to investigate themselves.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52678815e4b027bac8ef99f1\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T09:39:07.419+01:00\">9.39am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Nick Herbert</strong>, the Conservative former policing minister, gave an interview to the Today programme about the &quot;plebgate&quot; case. Here are the main points. I've taken the quotes from <a href=\"http://www.politicshome.com\">PoliticsHome.</a></p> <p><strong>• Herbert said the reputation of the entire police was at stake.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The vast majority of officers can rightly feel aggrieved that, actually, the service is tarred by this behaviour. And I think the failure of the service collectively to grip this, to demonstrate that they think that officers who give a false account is unacceptable or shouldn't be sanctioned appropriately, I think that is incredibly damaging to public confidence in the police, and it is up to them this afternoon and going forwards to demonstrate they are running the service in a proper manner.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• Herbert said the disciplinary inquiry into the three officers should be re-opened.</strong></p> <p><strong>• He said a suggestion in the Times from David Davis, the Conservative MP and a close friend of Andrew Mitchell's,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/23/plebgate-david-davis-surveillance-police\"> that the police should be fitted with cameras and microphones to record all contact with members of the public </a>was &quot;worth piloting&quot;.</strong></p> <p><strong>• He criticised Ron Ball, the Warwickshire police and crime commissioner, for <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24627319#TWEET931351\">saying that Andrew Mitchell's friends have been &quot;baying for blood&quot; over the affair.</a></strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I think that's a spectacularly ill-judged comment given that these findings were made by the Independent Police Complaints Commission ... His job as the elected police and crime commissioner is to hold his force to account. Of course we want to get to the truth of this matter, but he needs to remember he should act in the public interest.</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-32dc377e-e51e-4d3a-bc6c-a78f41f1c60c\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/23/1382517515731/fd9867f9-a5bc-4539-b6fd-6e106c6d8449-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Nick Herbert.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Nick Herbert. Photograph: Eamonn McCabe</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526785d3e4b0bdde19a21127\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T09:24:27.796+01:00\">9.24am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Norman Smith (who interviewed Keith Vaz this morning) also says the committee will publish the first draft of the report into the conduct of the three Police Federation officers accused of giving a misleading account of their meeting with Andrew Mitchell, as well as the final report.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392922322710958080\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>I understand Home Affairs Committee will release both police reports - draft and final report - into <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23plebgate&amp;src=hash\">#plebgate</a> meeting with Andrew Mitchell</p>— norman smith (@BBCNormanS) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392922322710958080\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>The original report was written by&nbsp;Jerry Wreakes-Williams, who is giving evidence to the committee this afternoon. <a href=\"http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/focus/article1329591.ece\">According to the Sunday Times (paywall),</a> he was unhappy that his decision to recommend disciplinary action against the three officers were over-ruled by more senior officers.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>This newspaper has now been told that the senior officer who wrote the initial report on Mitchell’s Sutton Coldfield meeting, Jerry Wreakes-Williams, has privately expressed his disquiet about the actions of the superiors who overruled his recommendation that Hinton, Jones and MacKaill be disciplined. “He is not happy. But he has to accept the decisions of his superiors,” said a source close to&nbsp;the case. </p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526784dce4b027bac8ef99ee\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T09:15:56.132+01:00\">9.15am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong>, the chair of the home affairs committee, told BBC News this morning that the role of this committee was to establish the facts. I've taken the quote from <a href=\"http://www.politicshome.com\">PoliticsHome.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We’re not a peace council, we’re a committee of parliament, and our role is to establish the facts and see where the facts lead. Of course there are others who wish to be making comments and wish to involved and it’s always helpful to have them as part of the debate. But at the end of the day what the committee will do is listen to evidence and come to a conclusion as to how we think the best solution to this agonisingly difficult problem is so that there is closure and people can move forward.</p> </blockquote> <p>It’s not just about one case: this has got wider implications about the integrity of and trust in the police and I think it’s important that we deliberate carefully, listen to the facts and come to a conclusion.</p> <p>Vaz said his committee may also want to take evidence from others before it publishes a report.</p> <p>According to the BBC's Norman Smith, the committee will report next week.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392921870401413120\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23plebgate&amp;src=hash\">#plebgate</a> report by Home Affairs Committee will be published next week</p>— norman smith (@BBCNormanS) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/statuses/392921870401413120\">October 23, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5267827ee4b0bdde19a21125\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-23T09:04:53.480+01:00\">9.04am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Thank God for Keith Vaz. He may have been an indifferent government minister, and he would win an Olympic medal for vanity, but when it comes to chairing the home affairs select committee, and asserting the committee's right to stick its nose into any matter vaguely home affairs-related, and haul people in at short notice for a grilling, he has been hard to fault. Today we are going to get a classic example because the committee is going to take evidence from<a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24629610\"> the three Police Federation officers accused of giving a misleading account of their meeting with Andrew Mitchell about the “plebgate” affair,</a> the officer who investigated whether this amounted to misconduct, the three chief constables who decided not to take disciplinary action against them, and the Independent Police Complaints Commission, which decided that that decision was a mistake. In other words we're going to get a full inquiry into this controversy, concluded in the course of an afternoon. A few years ago Commons select committees were wary of engaging in this kind of micro-scrutiny, but Vaz and some of today's other select committee chairmen are bolder. It has been a good development for those who like to see parliament asserting its power. And, of course, it makes for great copy.</p> <p>I will write more about the background to the hearing before it starts. Although the session will just focus on what three relatively junior officers said after a meeting with the then Conservative chief whip, the ramifications spread much further, and what happens this afternoon may well affect the reputation of the entire police.</p> <p>Before that, of course, we've got PMQs. Here's the agenda for the day.</p> <p><em>9.20am:</em> Owen Paterson, the environment secretary, gives evidence to the Commons environmental audit committee on biodiversity offsetting.</p> <p><em>9.30am:</em> David Laws, the schools minister, gives evidence to the Commons education committee on school place.</p> <p><em>10.30am:</em> Christopher Jeffries, the Leveson inquiry witness, gives evidence to the Lords committee on public inquiries.</p> <p><em>12pm:</em> David Cameron and Ed Miliband clash at PMQs.</p> <p><em>2.45pm:</em> Dame Anne Owers, chair of the Independent Police Complaints Commission, and Deborah Glass, the IPCC's deputy chair, give evidence to the Commons home affairs committee about the “plebgate” controversy. At 3.15pm Chief Inspector Jerry Reakes-Williams, from Professional Standards for Warwickshire and West Mercia Police, gives evidence. At 3.45pm Detective Sergeant Stuart Hinton from Warwickshire Police Federation, Sergeant Chris Jones from West Midlands Police Federation and Inspector Ken MacKaill from West Mercia Police Federation give evidence. And at 4.30pm Chief Constable Andy Parker from Warwickshire Police, Chief Constable David Shaw from West Mercia Police and Chief Constable Chris Sims from West Midlands Police give evidence.</p> <p><em>4.30pm:</em> Cameron meets the Burmese opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi in Downing Street.</p> <p>As usual, I’ll also be covering all the breaking political news as well as looking at the papers and bringing you the best politics from the web. I’ll post a lunchtime summary after PMQs and another after the home affairs committee hearing.</p> <p>If you want to follow me on Twitter, I’m on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AndrewSparrow\">@AndrewSparrow.</a></p> </div> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420725354|2013-10-23T17:15:08Z|a70ddd098b99f6d127607baa86dd2d0d7345d8b2 -->",
