      "id":"politics/2013/oct/18/michael-portillo-andrew-mitchell-pleb",
      "sectionId":"politics",
      "sectionName":"Politics",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-18T14:58:35Z",
      "webTitle":"Michael Portillo withdraws claim Mitchell used 'pleb' in private speech",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/18/michael-portillo-andrew-mitchell-pleb",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2013/oct/18/michael-portillo-andrew-mitchell-pleb",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"4",
        "trailText":"<p>Ex-minister says he got 'carried away' over claims made on BBC1's This Week programme regarding former chief whip</p>",
        "headline":"Michael Portillo withdraws claim Mitchell used 'pleb' in private speech",
        "body":"<p><a href=\"http://www.michaelportillo.co.uk\" title=\"\">Michael Portillo</a> has retracted a claim that he had heard <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/andrew-mitchell\" title=\"\">Andrew Mitchell</a> use the word pleb in private conversation.</p><p>The former minister turned political commentator and broadcaster said he got \"carried away\" and had \"misspoken\" in a television discussion on the so-called Plebgate row on Thursday night.</p><p>Mitchell has admitted swearing in the presence of officers guarding Downing Street but denied using the word plebs.</p><p>Portillo told <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24576413\" title=\"\">BBC1's This Week.</a> :\"I have heard him [Mitchell] use that word in private conversation – the pleb word, I mean. I didn't believe he could have used it at the gates [of Downing Street].\"</p><p>Pressed by the presenter Andrew Neil on whether he had really heard Mitchell use it, Portillo said: \"I think I did, but not in a bad context. Some policeman thought: 'Ah, that's a word that people will believe that Andrew Mitchell could have used.' But he wouldn't have used it in that context.\"</p><p>Portillo, who defended Mitchell in the immediate aftermath of the Downing Street incident last year <a href=\"http://www.itv.com/news/update/2012-09-24/michael-portillo-difficult-for-david-cameron-to-give-chief-whip-stern-talking-to/\" title=\"\">when the government was initially more cautious,</a> withdrew the pleb word claim on Friday, after his remarks were widely reported.</p><p>\"I seem to have misspoken,\" he said. \"I had no right to say that.\"</p><p>He added: \"I think I got carried away in the heat of the moment. I did not mean to say it and I want to withdraw it.\"</p><p>The Crown Prosecution Service is considering whether criminal charges should be brought following a Scotland Yard investigation into claims that officers conspired against Mitchell.</p><p>A furious row broke out between police and politicians this week, following suggestions that three members of the Police Federation gave misleading versions of a meeting they had with Mitchell following the incident in Downing Street. David Cameron has called their conduct \"not acceptable\" and <a href=\"www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/16/andrew-mitchell-apology-plebgate-david-cameron-police\" title=\"\">said Mitchell is owed an apology</a>.</p><p>Deborah Glass, deputy chairman of the <a href=\"http://www.ipcc.gov.uk\" title=\"\">Independent Police Complaints Commission</a>, has called for a <a href=\"http://www.ipcc.gov.uk/news/ipcc-disagrees-findings-west-mercia-investigation-conduct-police-federation-representatives\" title=\"\">misconduct panel to decide on the three officers' behaviour.</a> She said in an email to senior officers that a police investigation originally concluded the three had a case to answer for misconduct over the meeting with Mitchell, but that decision was later reversed.</p><p>Bob Jones, police and crime commissioner for West Midlands, one of the forces involved in the row, has demanded an explanation from the IPCC's chair Anne Owers.</p><p>He wrote: \"I would hope your further investigation into the assertion in Deborah Glass's letter, which has led to media speculation that senior officers interfered with the investigating officer's report, would show that this is a gross distortion of what actually took place.\"</p><p>He also criticised the IPCC's press statement on the issue. \"If I was to make an analogy with the criminal justice process, the <a href=\"http://www.ipcc.gov.uk/news/ipcc-disagrees-findings-west-mercia-investigation-conduct-police-federation-representatives\" title=\"\">press release </a>is akin to a police officer commenting after a trial that the accused was, despite being acquitted, guilty as hell.</p><p>\"Your deputy's actions have led to a position where the integrity and honesty of the investigating teams she was supervising have been vilified in parliament and the media.\"</p><p>West Mercia is reviewing its investigation.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420354185|2013-10-23T17:15:08Z|2d5a6ed892bd00685e1b5d5841b88e80f7c8e265 -->",
